{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"62f09fc8-df85-4826-9de0-106ee1c5553c","content":"No repo-specific docs on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\nOn macOS, when `createdump` isn't bundled (common with NativeAOT), you can still get crash dumps:\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n2. **Find the crash report:** macOS writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name.\n\n3. **Get a core file:** Core files go to `/cores/core.<pid>`. Verify the directory exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n5. **If `/cores` is empty**, macOS SIP may be blocking core dumps for signed binaries. You can:\n   - Codesign with entitlements: `com.apple.security.get-task-allow = true`\n   - Or disable SIP temporarily (not recommended in production).\n\n**Key point:** NativeAOT apps don't include `createdump` because they compile to native code directly — use the standard macOS/lldb crash analysis workflow instead of .NET-specific tooling.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9fb12aa1-6dab-42b1-9182-d6da489eb14c","outputTokens":377,"requestId":"6806:2F39F8:AE65631:BD88F41:69FD4236"},"id":"aa7c5483-5998-42fc-98c6-e82f850403f0","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:54:09.230Z","parentId":"fb1333c0-ed08-475a-b9ee-996617442954"}
